<DOC><DOCNO> AP880714-0213 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 2343EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     07-14 0185</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Salvador,0188</SECOND><HEAD>Leftist Rebels Call Transport Ban In El Salvador</HEAD><DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Leftist guerrillas battling theU.S.-backed government of President Jose Napoleon Duarte announcedon Thursday a transport ban on roads and highways nationwidebeginning at midnight.   The ban was the fourth this year by guerrillas of the FarabundoMarti National Liberation Front coalition and was announced in abroadcast over their clandestine Radio Venceremos, monitored inthis capital city.   The rebels said it was in response to security forces' use oftear gas and clubs Tuesday to break up a demonstration of peasantsfrom farming cooperatives. The armed forces claimed thedemonstrators provoked the repression by damaging vehicles andhitting soldiers.   In the broadcast, the guerrillas also promised to step upsabotage of the electrical distribution system. The rebelsregularly blow up high-tension line towers and utility poles toblack out whole sectors of the country.   The transport bans usually last three days. Previous suchprohibitions succeeded in reducing nationwide road transport by upto 90 percent. The guerrillas stopped and burned or fired onvehicles violating the ban.</TEXT></DOC>